  <h2>Understanding What Wine Goes With Salmon</h2>
  <p>When it comes to what wine goes with salmon, quality matters more than price. Our team of sommeliers has tasted hundreds of options to bring you these expert recommendations.</p>

  <h2>Perfect Food Pairings</h2>

<h3>Why Salmon and Wine Work So Beautifully Together</h3>
<p>Salmon's rich, fatty texture and delicate protein structure create an ideal canvas for wine pairing. The fish's natural oils require wines with sufficient acidity to cleanse the palate—think of how lemon cuts through butter. Meanwhile, salmon's moderate protein content won't overpower delicate wines like beef might, yet provides enough substance to support medium-bodied selections. The key lies in matching the wine's weight to the salmon's richness while considering preparation methods that can dramatically alter the pairing equation.</p>

<h3>Classic Pairings That Never Fail</h3>
<p><strong>Pinot Noir from Oregon or Burgundy</strong> represents the gold standard for salmon pairings. The wine's bright acidity cuts through the fish's natural oils while its silky tannins complement rather than compete with the delicate protein. A 2019 Willamette Valley Pinot Noir, with its cherry fruit and earthy undertones, mirrors salmon's complexity without overwhelming it.</p>

<p><strong>Chardonnay, particularly from Chablis or Sonoma Coast</strong>, brings mineral-driven acidity and subtle oak that enhances salmon's natural flavors. The wine's creamy texture matches the fish's richness, while citrus notes provide the essential acidic contrast. A premier cru Chablis like Montée de Tonnerre offers the perfect balance of weight and freshness.</p>

<h3>Modern Creative Combinations</h3>
<p><strong>Austrian Riesling</strong> has emerged as a contemporary favorite, especially with Asian-inspired salmon preparations. The wine's petrol notes and lime-like acidity complement ginger and soy-based marinades beautifully. Try a Grüner Veltliner from the Wachau—its white pepper spice and mineral backbone create fascinating flavor bridges.</p>

<p><strong>Rosé from Provence or Bandol</strong> offers versatility for summer salmon dishes. The wine's strawberry fruit and herb de Provence notes complement cedar-plank grilled salmon, while its crisp acidity handles rich preparations like salmon burgers or tacos.</p>

<h3>How Cooking Methods Transform Pairings</h3>
<p><strong>Grilled salmon</strong> develops smoky, caramelized flavors that call for wines with more structure—think Côtes du Rhône Rouge or California Syrah. The charring creates umami compounds that pair beautifully with earthy, peppery wines.</p>

<p><strong>Poached or steamed salmon</strong> retains delicate flavors best matched with lighter wines like Albariño from Rías Baixas or German Riesling Kabinett. These preparations preserve the fish's subtle character, requiring wines that won't mask its elegance.</p>

<p><strong>Smoked salmon</strong> demands wines with enough intensity to match its concentrated flavors—Champagne's bubbles and acidity cut through the richness while complementing the brine-cured character.</p>

<h3>Sauce Considerations</h3>
<p><strong>Hollandaise or cream-based sauces</strong> require wines with higher acidity—white Burgundy or Loire Valley Sauvignon Blanc provide the necessary contrast to rich, buttery preparations.</p>

<p><strong>Asian glazes with soy, mirin, or miso</strong> pair exceptionally with off-dry Riesling or Gewürztraminer, whose slight sweetness balances umami intensity while their acidity maintains freshness.</p>

<h3>Pairings to Avoid</h3>
<p>High-tannin reds like Cabernet Sauvignon clash with salmon's delicate proteins, creating metallic, bitter flavors. Similarly, heavily oaked Chardonnays can overwhelm subtle preparations, while very light wines like basic Pinot Grigio lack the structure to complement richer salmon dishes.</p>

