<h2>Expert Tips</h2>
<ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-4 text-gray-700">
  <li><strong>Match Wine Weight to Salmon Preparation Method</strong> - Wild salmon's leaner texture pairs beautifully with medium-bodied wines like Oregon Pinot Noir or white Burgundy, while rich farmed Atlantic salmon can handle fuller wines such as Côtes du Rhône or oaked Chardonnay. The key is matching the wine's body to the fish's richness rather than simply following red-with-meat rules.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Serve Pinot Noir Slightly Chilled at 60-62°F</strong> - When pairing Pinot Noir with salmon, serve it cooler than typical red wine service temperature. This slight chill enhances the wine's natural acidity, which cuts through salmon's oils while preventing the tannins from overwhelming the delicate fish proteins. Use a wine thermometer for precision.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Skip Decanting for Most Salmon-Friendly Wines</strong> - The elegant, medium-bodied wines that pair best with salmon—like Sancerre, Chablis, or young Pinot Noir—don't benefit from decanting. Their delicate aromatics can actually be diminished by excessive aeration. Only decant mature Burgundy (10+ years) if it shows sediment.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Choose Burgundy Glasses for Both Red and White Pairings</strong> - The tulip shape of a Burgundy glass concentrates the subtle aromatics crucial in salmon pairings, whether you're serving Chablis or Pinot Noir. Avoid large Bordeaux glasses that disperse delicate floral and mineral notes that complement salmon's clean flavor profile.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Consider Salmon's Natural Oils When Selecting Acidity Levels</strong> - Salmon's omega-3 fatty acids require wines with bright acidity to cleanse the palate. Look for wines with naturally high acid levels: Sancerre (12.5-13% alcohol), Chablis Premier Cru, or cool-climate Riesling. The malic and tartaric acids literally cut through fish oils, refreshing your palate between bites.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Time Your Wine Opening Based on Cooking Method</strong> - Open delicate whites like Muscadet or Albariño just before serving raw or lightly cooked salmon preparations. For grilled or cedar-plank salmon, open medium-bodied reds 15-20 minutes before serving to allow slight softening of tannins while preserving fresh fruit character.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Age Matters: Choose Young, Fresh Wines Over Mature Bottles</strong> - Salmon's clean, oceanic flavors are best complemented by wines with vibrant primary fruit and mineral characteristics. Serve Chablis within 5-7 years, Loire Valley Sauvignon Blanc within 3-4 years, and Pinot Noir within 6-8 years. Aged wines with developed tertiary flavors can overpower salmon's subtle taste.</li>
  
  <li><strong>Account for Sauce Pairings in Your Wine Selection</strong> - The sauce often dictates the wine choice more than the salmon itself. Lemon-butter sauces call for crisp Sancerre, hollandaise demands rich Chardonnay, teriyaki glazes work with off-dry Riesling, and herb crusts pair with Sauvignon Blanc. Always taste your complete dish—salmon plus accompaniments—when making final wine decisions.</li>
</ol>



