    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the difference between wines for grilled versus poached salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Grilled salmon develops caramelized, smoky flavors that pair beautifully with medium-bodied reds like Pinot Noir or Grenache, while poached salmon's delicate preparation calls for lighter wines like Sancerre or unoaked Chardonnay. The cooking method significantly impacts the salmon's flavor intensity—grilling adds char and complexity that can handle more robust wines. Poached salmon retains its natural oils and subtle taste, requiring wines that won't overpower these nuanced flavors.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Should I serve wine with salmon chilled or at room temperature?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">White wines should be served well-chilled at 45-50°F to complement salmon's rich oils and enhance the wine's acidity, while light reds like Pinot Noir should be slightly chilled at 55-60°F. This cooler temperature for reds helps balance the wine's tannins against salmon's fatty texture and prevents the alcohol from overwhelming the fish's delicate flavors. Room temperature reds can taste overly heavy and alcoholic when paired with seafood.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What wine goes with salmon teriyaki or Asian-glazed preparations?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Sweet and umami-rich glazes require wines with good acidity and a touch of residual sugar, making off-dry Riesling or Gewürztraminer excellent choices. The wine's sweetness balances the soy and mirin in teriyaki, while the acidity cuts through the salmon's richness. For a red option, try a fruit-forward Beaujolais or Oregon Pinot Noir, which have enough brightness to complement Asian flavors without clashing with the sweet-savory profile.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Is Sauvignon Blanc or Chardonnay better with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Both work wonderfully, but the choice depends on your salmon preparation and personal preference for wine weight. Sauvignon Blanc's crisp acidity and herbaceous notes excel with simply prepared salmon, cedar plank cooking, or dishes with herbs like dill or capers. Chardonnay, especially with some oak, complements richer preparations like salmon with cream sauces or butter-based dishes, as its fuller body and vanilla notes enhance the fish's natural oils.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's a good budget wine under $15 that pairs with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Look for Columbia Crest Sauvignon Blanc from Washington State or Bogle Pinot Noir from California, both typically under $15 and excellent with salmon. Portuguese Vinho Verde offers incredible value at $8-12, providing crisp acidity and mineral notes that complement grilled or cedar plank salmon beautifully. These wines prove you don't need to spend heavily to achieve great salmon pairings—focus on wines with good acidity and appropriate body weight rather than prestige labels.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Can I pair sparkling wine with salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Absolutely—sparkling wine creates exceptional salmon pairings, especially with smoked salmon, sushi, or cream-based preparations. Champagne's acidity cuts through salmon's oils while its bubbles cleanse the palate, and Crémant de Loire or Cava offer more affordable alternatives with similar benefits. The effervescence particularly shines with rich salmon dishes like eggs Benedict with smoked salmon or salmon mousse, where the bubbles provide textural contrast and palate refreshment.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What's the biggest mistake people make when choosing wine for salmon?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is selecting wines that are too heavy or tannic, which clash with salmon's delicate oils and can create an unpleasant metallic taste. Many people automatically choose full-bodied Cabernet Sauvignon or heavily oaked Chardonnay, overwhelming the fish's subtle flavors. Instead, focus on wines with good acidity and moderate body—think Pinot Noir instead of Malbec, or Loire Valley whites instead of big California Chardonnays.</p>
  </div>
  
  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">Are there good non-alcoholic wine alternatives for salmon pairings?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">High-quality dealcoholized Sauvignon Blanc or Pinot Grigio work surprisingly well, maintaining the acidity needed to complement salmon's richness without the alcohol. Brands like Ariel and Fre produce dealcoholized wines that retain much of their original character through careful production methods. For a completely different approach, consider premium sparkling water with citrus or elderflower flavoring, which provides the palate-cleansing acidity that makes wine such a natural salmon companion.</p>
